.TH simple_shell 1 "November 2025" "1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
simple_shell \- a small UNIX command interpreter (executable: hsh)

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
.br
.B echo "command" | hsh

.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B simple_shell
program implements a minimal subset of the
.BR /bin/sh (1)
command interpreter.

It supports interactive and non-interactive execution, command parsing,
PATH lookup, and several built-in commands.  
The project follows Holberton School requirements and is fully Betty-compliant.

---

.SH TASKS OVERVIEW
The following summarizes the features implemented across the project tasks:

.TP
.B Task 0 - README, man, AUTHORS
Prepare project documentation including:
.br
\- A complete README file.
.br
\- A manual page named
.BR man_1_simple_shell .
.br
\- An AUTHORS file listing contributors in the format:
.br
"Name <email> - role".

.TP
.B Task 1 - Betty compliance
All source files must follow Betty style rules.
No more than 5 functions may appear in a single file.

.TP
.B Task 2 - Simple Shell 0.1
Display a prompt, read a command, execute it using
.BR fork (2)
and
.BR execve (2) .
Loop until EOF or the user enters
.BR exit .

.TP
.B Task 3 - Simple Shell 0.2
If a command contains no '/', search for it in directories listed in
.B PATH .
If not found, print an error:
.br
.EX
hsh: line_number: command: not found
.EE

.TP
.B Task 4 - Simple Shell 0.3
Handle end-of-file (Ctrl+D) gracefully without crashes or infinite loops.

.TP
.B Task 5 - Simple Shell 0.4
Implement:
.br
.BR "exit [n]" .
If
.I n
is not a valid number, print an error:
.br
.EX
exit
hsh: line_number: exit: Illegal number: n
.EE
The shell must continue running and return status code 2.

.TP
.B Task 6 - Simple Shell 1.0
Implement the
.B env
built-in command to print the current environment (using
.BR environ ).

.TP
.B Task 13 - setenv, unsetenv
Add two built-in commands to manage environment variables:

.RS
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBsetenv VARIABLE VALUE\fR  
Create or update an environment variable.  
Print an error to stderr on failure.

.IP \[bu]
\fBunsetenv VARIABLE\fR  
Remove an environment variable.  
Print an error to stderr on failure.
.RE

---

.SH BUILT-INS

.TP
.B env
Print all environment variables, one per line.

.TP
.B exit [n]
Exit the shell with status
.I n
(modulo 256).  
Invalid arguments set status 2 and do not exit.

.TP
.B setenv VARIABLE VALUE
Create or update an environment variable.

.TP
.B unsetenv VARIABLE
Remove an existing environment variable.

---

.SH USAGE

.SS Interactive mode
.EX
$ ./hsh
($) /bin/ls
README.md shell.h main.c
($) env
($) exit
.EE

.SS Non-interactive mode
.EX
$ echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
README.md shell.h main.c
.EE

---

.SH ERRORS

If a command is not found:
.EX
hsh: line_number: command: not found
.EE

Invalid numeric argument to exit:
.EX
exit
hsh: line_number: exit: Illegal number: abc
.EE

Errors in setenv or unsetenv:
.EX
hsh: line_number: setenv: Missing arguments
hsh: line_number: unsetenv: Variable not found
.EE

---

.SH EXIT STATUS
The shell exits with the status of the last executed command.  
Invalid arguments to
.B exit
set the status to 2 without terminating the shell.

---

.SH FILES
.TP
.B README.md
Project documentation.
.TP
.B AUTHORS
Contributor list.
.TP
.B shell.h
Header file containing structure definitions and prototypes.
.TP
.B builtins.c
Built-in commands:
.BR env ,
.BR exit ,
.BR setenv ,
and
.BR unsetenv .
.TP
.B path.c
Command resolution using the PATH variable.
.TP
.B exec.c
Process creation and execution logic.
.TP
.B parser.c , helpers.c , utils*.c
Input parsing and utility helpers.

---

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR sh (1),
.BR execve (2),
.BR fork (2),
.BR getenv (3)

